Title: The Crossing
Credit: Julie and the Phantoms — Unofficial Season 1 Finale
Author: A fan continuation
Draft date: Personal project
Notes: Resolves the Season 1 cliffhanger. PG family musical. Centerpiece song "Don't Let Go."

====

> JULIE AND THE PHANTOMS <

> "THE CROSSING" <

===

= TEASER

INT. MOLINA GARAGE STUDIO - NIGHT

Fairy lights. A half-eaten bag of chips. JULIE MOLINA (15) stands in the middle of the room, arms still out — because they are wrapped around LUKE (17, forever). He's solid. Real. Both of them frozen, terrified to move and break it.

REGGIE and ALEX hover close, not breathing (they don't have to).

REGGIE
Uh. Are you guys gonna stand like that all night, or—

ALEX
(hushed)
Reggie. She's *touching* him.

JULIE
(barely)
I'm touching him.

LUKE
You're touching me.

She pokes his shoulder. Pokes it again. Laughs — a wet, amazed laugh.

JULIE
We played the Orpheum. And I can— I can feel you.

LUKE
(grinning)
We played the Orpheum.

REGGIE
WE PLAYED THE ORPHEUM!

The boys whoop. Reggie tries to high-five Alex and his hand passes clean through.

REGGIE (CONT'D)
...Okay, so it's just Julie. Cool. Cool cool cool. Not jealous.

Julie steps back to really look at them — her impossible boys, glowing faintly with stage-light that isn't there anymore.

JULIE
So if we crossed over— wait. We *didn't* cross over. We played the Orpheum and you're all still—

LUKE
Here.

JULIE
Here.

A beat of pure, dumb joy.

Then —

Luke gasps. Doubles. A jagged BLUE-WHITE light stutters under the skin of his wrist, where the stamp is.

The garage lights BLOW. Sparks. Reggie and Alex seize at the same instant, gripping their own wrists.

JULIE (CONT'D)
Luke?! Luke—

She grabs for him — and this time her hands pass THROUGH. Gone solid. Gone again. He flickers like bad film.

LUKE
(through his teeth)
It's— the stamp— it's never been this—

The jolt releases them. The three boys drop, shaking. The lights buzz back, dim and wrong.

ALEX
(small)
That was worse. That was so much worse.

Julie kneels in the middle of them, hands hovering, useless.

JULIE
Okay. Okay. We're gonna fix this. We are going to *fix this.*

CUT TO:

EXT. MOLINA HOUSE - FRONT WALK - CONTINUOUS

NICK (16) stands alone on the dark sidewalk, staring up at Julie's window. Sweet kid. Wrong stillness.

A shape resolves out of the streetlight haze behind him: CALEB COVINGTON (ageless, immaculate, a smile like a velvet rope).

CALEB
How sweet. The broken-hearted boy. Fighting for his girl.

NICK
(turning, foggy)
...Do I know you?

CALEB
You will.

Caleb's stamp FLARES gold. Light pours into Nick. Nick straightens — and the sweetness drains out of his eyes, replaced by something old and amused.

NICK/CALEB
I have a fight too.

He smiles up at Julie's window. Tips an invisible hat.

NICK/CALEB (CONT'D)
Hi, Nick.

SMASH TO BLACK.

> MAIN TITLES <

= END OF TEASER

= ACT ONE

INT. MOLINA KITCHEN - MORNING

Sunlight. Normalcy, weaponized. RAY MOLINA flips an egg with the confidence of a man who will not land it. CARLOS (12) sits at the counter behind a homemade device: a smoke detector duct-taped to a flashlight duct-taped to his sister's old baby monitor.

RAY
Carlos. What is that.

CARLOS
EMF reader. Paranormal activity in this house is up four hundred percent.

RAY
Mm. And down four hundred percent in doing the dishes.

Carlos waves the device at the garage-facing window. It SHRIEKS. He gasps. Ray drops the egg.

CARLOS
DID YOU HEAR THAT—

RAY
That's the smoke detector, mijo. Because of the eggs. That I am now scraping off the floor.

Julie comes down, hollow-eyed, having clearly not slept. She kisses Ray's cheek.

RAY (CONT'D)
There she is. Big Orpheum hologram star. People are still talking about that show, you know. The *hologram boys.* Your tía thinks it's CGI. I told her, "Marisol, my daughter is an artist."

JULIE
(faint smile)
Thanks, Dad.

RAY
(beat, gentler)
You okay? You've got your mom's face on. The one she made when a song wasn't done yet.

That lands harder than he knows. Julie holds it together.

JULIE
Just... the song's not done yet.

She grabs a banana and bolts for the garage. Carlos's EMF reader screams the whole way.

CARLOS
(vindicated, to Ray)
ARTIST. Sure.

CUT TO:

EXT. SKATE PARK - DAY

Empty bowl, hard light. ALEX sits on the lip, knees up. WILLIE (the world's most relaxed ghost) rolls up, drops his board, sits beside him — close.

ALEX
You came.

WILLIE
Caleb thinks I'm running an errand. I've got maybe ten minutes before he—
(he winces; his own stamp pulses)
—before he notices.

ALEX
Willie. Last night. It nearly... we nearly *went out.* Like a light. Like nothing.

Willie can't look at him.

WILLIE
That's what I came to tell you. The stamp doesn't just hurt anymore. You're past the warnings. Caleb's giving you till the dark of the moon — tonight, sundown. After that the stamp finishes it. You don't cross over, you don't join him... you cease. Not the good kind of gone. *Not anywhere.*

ALEX
(very quietly)
Cool. Cool cool cool.

WILLIE
There's one way out. The way out there always was. You finish your unfinished business — the real one — and you cross over. Crossing over burns the stamp right off you. Caleb can't follow you where that light goes.

ALEX
But the Orpheum *was* our unfinished business. We've been chasing that gig for twenty-five years. We played it. And we're still here.

WILLIE
(meeting his eyes)
Then it was never the gig, Alex.

A beat between them — the kind that wants to be a first kiss and can't be, not yet.

WILLIE (CONT'D)
Figure out what it really is. Before sundown.
(standing, board under foot)
And whatever you do tonight... don't let him get you on that stage of his. Once you're stamped *in,* you're his forever.

ALEX
Willie—

But he's gone. Just the board's echo in the empty bowl.

CUT TO:

INT. MOLINA GARAGE STUDIO - DAY

Julie, Flynn, and the boys. FLYNN (15, loyal, lethal) paces with a whiteboard marker like a general.

FLYNN
Okay. Band meeting. Living members present, dead members present-ish. We have one problem and it's a big translucent problem.

She writes: UNFINISHED BUSINESS = ??? and SUNDOWN.

REGGIE
I've been thinking about it all night. What if our unfinished business is that I never learned to do a backflip?

ALEX
It's not the backflip, Reggie.

REGGIE
What if it's that *you* never told me I couldn't do a backflip and now I'll never know—

LUKE
(focused, intense — mission mode)
It's bigger than us. It has to be. We spent our whole lives — our whole *deaths* — thinking the dream was the stage. The lights. Being seen. But we got seen. We got the Orpheum. And it didn't finish anything.
(he turns to Julie)
The only thing that's changed... is her.

The room goes quiet. Julie meets his eyes.

JULIE
Me.

LUKE
The day you played our song. That's when we got real. That's when any of this started to *mean* something.

FLYNN
(softly, writing)
"It's not the dream. It's the connection."
(beat)
That's a lyric, by the way. You're welcome.

Julie's looking past them — at the wall of her mother's old things. A box marked ROSE.

JULIE
(slow)
My mom. This was her studio.

REGGIE
We know. Best energy of any room we've ever haunted. Five stars.

JULIE
No — when did you guys put out your demo? Your one demo. Before the— before the hot dogs.

ALEX
'Ninety-five. We mailed like fifty cassettes to anyone with an address. Why?

Julie's already pulling the box down.

JULIE
Because my mom kept everything.

CUT TO:

= END OF ACT ONE

= ACT TWO

INT. MOLINA GARAGE STUDIO - CONTINUOUS

Julie digs through the ROSE box. Photos, set lists, a dried dahlia. Then — her hand stops.

She pulls out a faded cassette. Hand-lettered: **SUNSET CURVE — DESTINY.** And, paper-clipped to it, a worn, kid-sized T-shirt with the band's logo.

The boys go absolutely silent. Luke takes a step back like he's been struck.

LUKE
That's— Julie, that's our demo. That's *the* shirt. We only made a dozen.

REGGIE
(awed)
Your mom had a Sunset Curve shirt.

ALEX
Your mom was a *fan?*

Julie turns the cassette over. On the back, in her mother's young handwriting, a note:

JULIE
(reading)
"To the boys who I'll probably never meet — your music made me brave enough to write my own. Whatever happens, don't let it go. — R."

She lowers it. Tears standing.

JULIE (CONT'D)
She got your demo. In 'ninety-five. Your music made her start writing songs.
(beat, the whole thing landing)
The songs *I* play. The songs that brought you *here.*

LUKE
(barely)
Our music reached one person. One. And we thought we'd failed.

JULIE
You didn't fail. You reached her. She reached me. I reached *you.*
(she holds up the cassette)
This is the unfinished business. Not the stage. The *line* — your music to my mom to me to you. You finished it the second I sang your song. You just never got to *know* it.

A long, trembling silence. Reggie wipes his eyes on a sleeve that isn't real.

REGGIE
So... what you're saying is... we're gonna cross over.

The joy curdles. Because crossing over means—

ALEX
We're gonna cross over.

LUKE
(looking only at Julie)
And leave.

Julie can't answer. Flynn, in the doorway, lowers the whiteboard.

CUT TO:

INT. TREVOR WILSON'S MANSION - GREAT ROOM - DAY

A shrine to a stolen life: platinum records, a vintage guitar under glass. CARRIE (15) sits on the stairs scrolling, bored, queen of nothing today.

The doorbell. She answers — and finds NICK on the step. Too calm. Smiling.

CARRIE
Nick? We broke up. You don't get to just—

NICK/CALEB
Carrie. I'm looking for your father. The famous Trevor Wilson.
(he steps in, uninvited, eyes drifting over the records)
A man who built a kingdom on other people's songs. I do admire the commitment.

CARRIE
(unsettled)
Okay, that's— Nick, you're being weird. Dad's not— what are you talking about?

From the study, TREVOR ("Bobby," now 45, soft and famous) appears.

TREVOR
Carrie? Who's at the—
(sees Nick; doesn't recognize the thing inside him, but feels it)
Can I help you, son?

NICK/CALEB
(pleasant)
Just admiring your work, Mr. Wilson. "Now or Never." "Bright." Real... *original* stuff.

He lets that hang. Trevor's smile falters — twenty-five years of guilt has a long fuse.

Carrie clocks her father's face. Files it away. Something's wrong here, and not just with Nick.

NICK/CALEB (CONT'D)
Tell the Phantoms I'll see them at sundown.

He leaves. Carrie and Trevor stand in the wreckage of a sentence neither will finish.

CARRIE
(quiet)
Dad. What songs.

TREVOR
(too fast)
Nothing, mija. Pop star drama. Go.

But she doesn't go. She looks at the guitar under glass like she's never really seen it.

CUT TO:

EXT. MOLINA HOUSE - BACKYARD - LATER

Julie and Luke, alone, on the back step. Sunlight slanting — the day burning down toward sundown. He's trying to be brave. So is she. Neither's good at it.

LUKE
Hey. So. We figured it out. That's a win. Bands would kill for this kind of clarity.

JULIE
(thick)
Don't do the joke.

LUKE
I'm not doing the joke, I'm doing the— okay it was a little bit the joke.

She laughs despite herself. He reaches over — and takes her hand. Solid. They both watch it like a miracle that's running out.

LUKE (CONT'D)
You know what kills me? Not the dying part. We're old pros. It's that I finally got to hold your hand and now I have to— I have to be a gentleman about it.

JULIE
Luke.

LUKE
The whole time we were chasing the Orpheum, I thought I knew what I wanted. To be huge. To be *heard.* Turns out I just wanted to be heard by *you.*
(beat)
I'd do all of it again. The dying. The twenty-five years in a dark garage. All of it. If it ended here. On this step. With this.

He lifts their joined hands a half-inch. It's everything. PG and devastating.

JULIE
(whisper)
Then don't go.

LUKE
If I don't, the stamp takes me somewhere worse than gone. If I do, I'm free — but I'm... gone the good way. There's no door where I stay, Julie. I looked. There's no door.

She presses her forehead to his. They breathe.

JULIE
Then we play the best last show anyone's ever played. And I will be okay.
(beat, breaking)
I'm a terrible liar.

LUKE
The worst. It's one of my favorite things about you.

CUT TO:

= END OF ACT TWO

= ACT THREE

INT. HOLLYWOOD GHOST CLUB - DAY

Gold and shadow and impossible chandeliers. CALEB — back in his own form now, Nick released somewhere to wander — runs scales on a grand piano like a man who owns time.

WILLIE enters, tense.

CALEB
(not turning)
You've been spending a lot of energy on that drummer, William.

WILLIE
I do errands. You said—

CALEB
I say a great many things.
(he turns, warm and terrible)
The boys have until sundown. They'll come to me — they always do, when the alternative is *nothing.* And when they do, they sign. And then I'll have the only act in the afterlife that the living can see without my help.
(savoring)
Do you know what I could *build* with that?

WILLIE
And if they cross over instead?

Caleb's smile thins.

CALEB
Then they slip a leash I spent a great deal of effort tying. I'd be... very disappointed. In all my employees.

He lets the threat sit on Willie like a hand on the shoulder. Willie holds his eyes — and for the first time, doesn't look away.

WILLIE
(quiet, deciding something)
Yeah. Wouldn't want that.

CUT TO:

INT. MOLINA GARAGE STUDIO - DUSK

The light is going amber and final. Flynn strings the last fairy light. Reggie tunes a bass that's tuned. Alex adjusts a cymbal for the ninth time. Nervous energy you could power a city with.

ALEX
Okay so worst-case scenario, we cease to exist. Best-case scenario, we cross over and *also* cease to— wait, those are the same—

REGGIE
(clapping his shoulders)
Buddy. Breathe. You don't even have lungs. It's free.

Alex laughs — surprised, grateful. Reggie pulls them all into a huddle, Julie included.

REGGIE (CONT'D)
Twenty-five years ago we got a bad hot dog before the biggest gig of our lives. And I just want to say — being dead with you guys was better than being alive with anybody else.
(beat)
Also I'm pretty sure I could've done the backflip.

ALEX
(wet laugh)
You could never have done the backflip.

LUKE
(to all of them)
One more. The best one. For Rose. For Julie. For the line.

He puts his hand in the center. Reggie's hand. Alex's. And Julie lays her solid, living hand on top of all three ghost-hands — and for this moment, they're all solid under hers.

JULIE
Sunset Curve.

LUKE
Julie and the Phantoms.

The garage door rolls up. Flynn's borrowed string lights spill onto the driveway, where a small crowd has gathered — neighbors, kids from school, drawn by Flynn's last-minute post. And at the back, half in shadow: CARRIE. And NICK, himself again, blinking like he just woke up.

And behind THEM, unseen by the living: CALEB. Arms folded. Patient.

CALEB
(to himself, delighted)
A farewell show. How perfectly tragic. By all means. Play your hearts out.
(softer, certain)
You'll come to me before that light ever opens. They always do.

Julie sits at the piano. Looks back at her boys. They pick up their instruments — the instruments tethered to their souls.

JULIE
(to the crowd, voice shaking, then steadying)
This one's called "Don't Let Go." It's the last one we'll ever play.
(beat)
Make it loud.

CUT TO:

= END OF ACT THREE

= ACT FOUR

INT./EXT. MOLINA GARAGE - PERFORMANCE - NIGHT

Julie plays. A single piano line — Rose's line, the one in her handwriting. The boys SHIMMER into full visibility, solid to every eye in the driveway. Gasps. Phones up. But Julie only sees them.

JULIE (SINGING)
~ I found you in the dark of a song my mother wrote
~ Three ghosts and a melody, a message in a note
~ I wasn't ready, I was barely holding on
~ Then you sang, and somehow all the broken parts came home

The band lifts in under her — Reggie's bass, Alex's kick. Luke crosses to a shared mic.

LUKE (SINGING)
~ We chased the lights for twenty-five long years
~ Turns out the dream was standing right back here
~ Not the stage, not the crowd, not the name in lights
~ Just one voice singing ours into the night

Julie and Luke, together, the duet blooming —

JULIE & LUKE (SINGING)
~ So don't let go, don't let go
~ If this is goodbye then let it show
~ Every word we never said, every road we'll never know
~ I'll carry you wherever I go — don't let go

The full band SLAMS in on the chorus. The driveway erupts. Reggie and Alex trade the bridge of their lives —

REGGIE & ALEX (SINGING)
~ We were here, we were loud, we were true
~ We were more than the worst thing we ever went through
~ If the light comes to take us, we'll go without fear
~ 'Cause the best of us is staying right here

On the last word, it begins: a WARM WHITE LIGHT, blooming at the edges of the three boys. The crossing-over light. Real this time. Final.

Caleb's smug smile FALTERS.

CALEB
No. No — they're not supposed to *want* it—

The boys keep playing INTO the light. Choosing it. Alex finds Willie's face in the crowd — WILLIE, who came after all — and Willie nods: *go.*

Julie sees the light taking them. Her voice cracks on the bridge — her solo, alone at the piano, the band glowing brighter, fading—

JULIE (SINGING)
~ I know you have to leave to be free
~ I know the door that opens isn't meant for me
~ But before the light, before you let go—
~ Let me hold you one more time, so I'll always know

And she stands. And she crosses the stage. And into the blinding white, she throws her arms around Luke—

— and her arms CLOSE. Around something SOLID.

The light SURGES — and then, instead of taking them up and away... it sinks *into* them. The stamp on Luke's wrist BURNS gold, then white, then — *gone.* Clean skin. The jolt-light dies forever.

The boys are still here. Solid in Julie's arms. Solid to the crowd. Free.

LUKE
(stunned, holding her back — actually holding her)
Julie. The light. It— it didn't take us.

JULIE
(laughing, crying)
Because your unfinished business was never to *leave.*
(she touches his face)
It was to be *seen.* To be loved. To *belong* somewhere.
(beat)
You finished it. And it kept you HERE.

REGGIE
(staring at his own un-stamped wrist)
I'm free. The stamp's— Alex, the stamp's GONE—

ALEX
(to Willie, across the crowd)
WILLIE—

Willie's own stamp flickers — and as Caleb's hold on the boys breaks, the backlash ROCKS Caleb himself.

CALEB
(staggering, his gold dimming)
Impossible. You can't be free and *stay.* That's not how the rules—

LUKE
(turning, fierce, glowing with stage-light)
Yeah, well. We never were great with rules.

Caleb's power — built on stamps, on the threat of *nothing* — has nothing left to hold over boys who chose love over fear and won. His form GUTTERS like a candle.

And inside the crowd, NICK gasps — the last of Caleb's grip tearing loose of him. He stumbles. Carrie catches his arm.

NICK
(blinking, himself)
Carrie? How did I— where—

CALEB
(retreating into shadow, furious, unbeaten but routed)
This isn't finished. There are other stages. Other songs.
(a last venomous smile)
I'll be seeing you.

And he's gone. Just smoke and a cold spot where a chandelier-light used to be.

The song's final chord rings out. The crowd goes WILD — they think it's the best hologram show in history. Only Julie's family knows it was a resurrection.

She holds her boys — all three solid, all three free — in the middle of the loudest, most alive night of anyone's death.

CUT TO:

= END OF ACT FOUR

= TAG

INT. MOLINA GARAGE STUDIO - LATER THAT NIGHT

The crowd's gone. Fairy lights and quiet. The band sprawled in the afterglow, giddy and exhausted.

ALEX
So we're... not dying. Tonight.

REGGIE
We're un-stamped, un-doomed, and apparently I can be hugged now? Julie, test it.

Julie hugs Reggie. He bursts into happy tears.

REGGIE (CONT'D)
(muffled)
Twenty-five years. Worth it.

The garage door creaks. CARLOS stands there in pajamas, EMF reader screaming in his hand, mouth open. He stares directly at the three glowing boys.

CARLOS
I KNEW IT—

The boys POOF out instantly. The room is empty except for Julie, mid-air-hug of nobody.

JULIE
(too casual)
...Hey, Carlos.

CARLOS
(deflating)
The readings were at MAXIMUM.

JULIE
Probably the eggs.

He glares, unconvinced, and retreats. The boys POOF back, wheezing with laughter.

EXT. MOLINA HOUSE - FRONT WALK - SAME

Carrie walks NICK home, both shaken, the night enormous around them.

NICK
I keep losing time. And the last thing I remember clearly is this... man. Saying he had a fight.

CARRIE
(quiet, changed)
Yeah. I think a lot of people around here have been fighting things they didn't tell anybody about.
(beat — thinking of her father, of a guitar under glass)
I'm gonna go ask my dad some questions.

She means it. The first crack in the queen bee — the start of a girl who wants the truth more than the crown.

INT. MOLINA GARAGE STUDIO - CONTINUOUS

Alex steps outside the open door, where WILLIE waits, board under his arm, free and unbound — Caleb's fall took the stamp off him too.

WILLIE
So. You didn't cease to exist.

ALEX
(grinning)
Cool, right?

WILLIE
Very cool.
(beat)
I quit my job, by the way. Turns out the boss got... let go.

Alex laughs. Willie holds out a hand. Alex takes it — solid, both of them, a small private miracle of their own. They sit on the step, shoulder to shoulder, watching the stars.

ANGLE ON: Julie and Luke, just inside, watching the others.

LUKE
So. We're staying.

JULIE
You're staying.

LUKE
There's gonna be questions. About how a hologram band hugs people now. Carlos owns a *machine.*

JULIE
We'll figure it out.
(beat, looking at him)
We always figure out the song.

He takes her hand. The "Stay." outro of their song hums in, just piano, just breath.

LUKE
(softly, the last line of the night)
Don't let go.

JULIE
(smiling, holding on)
Wasn't planning on it.

She rests her head on his shoulder — solid, warm, here. The fairy lights glow. Somewhere out past the city, a chandelier flickers cold and patient — a promise for another night.

But not tonight. Tonight, the band is whole.

SMASH TO BLACK.

> END OF EPISODE <
